Is this step by step? Basically you need to say, make an account in github.. that would be first step.. instead of saying.. make sure this or that.

Gemini said
You're right. Let's strip away the "options" and give you a single, linear path from zero to a live link.

Since you have a Netlify account, we will use the GitHub connection. This is the "gold standard" because whenever you change your JSX file, the UAT link updates automatically.

Step 1: Create a GitHub Account
Go to GitHub.com.

Click Sign up and follow the prompts to create your account.

Verify your email address.

Step 2: Create a Repository (The "Cloud Folder")
On your GitHub home page, click the green New button (or the + icon in the top right) to create a "Repository."

Give it a name (e.g., my-uat-project).

Keep it Public (it’s easier for a first-time setup).

Check the box that says Add a README file.

Click Create repository.

Step 3: Upload your JSX File
In your new repository, click the Add file button and select Upload files.

Drag and drop your project folder (which contains your .jsx files and your package.json) into the box.

Scroll down and click the green Commit changes button.

Step 4: Connect GitHub to Netlify
Log in to Netlify.

Click the Add new site button.

Select Import from an existing project.

Click the GitHub button. A popup will ask for permission; click Authorize.

Step 5: Select Your Project
You will see a list of your GitHub repositories. Click on the one you named in Step 2 (my-uat-project).

Netlify will automatically fill in the "Build settings" (it usually knows to use npm run build).

Click the Deploy [Project Name] button at the bottom.

Step 6: Get Your UAT Link
You will see a "Production deploys" progress bar. Wait about 1–2 minutes.

Once it says Published, look at the top of the page. You will see a link ending in .netlify.app.

That is your UAT link. You can send that URL to anyone.

One Vital "Peers-to-Peer" Check:
Does your project have a file named package.json in the main folder?

Netlify needs that file to know it's a React project. If you only have a single .jsx file sitting by itself without that setup, the build will fail.

