Gemini said
Looking at your screenshot, your site is technically "Published" (as seen in the green badge under Production Deploys), but the reason it's showing "No Page Found" is exactly what we suspected: Netlify is looking for an HTML file to display, but all it sees is a raw JSX file.

Browsers cannot run JSX. You need to tell Netlify how to turn that JSX into a real website. Here is the step-by-step fix to get your "digitq" project working:

Step 1: Check your local files
For Netlify to host a React project, your GitHub repository must have these three things in the main folder:

package.json: This tells Netlify "I am a React app."

index.html: The entry point for the browser.

Your .jsx files: Inside a src folder.

If you only uploaded a single .jsx file to GitHub, it will never work.

Step 2: The "Quick Fix" (Use a Build Tool)
The easiest way to fix this is to use a tool called Vite. Run these commands in your terminal on your computer to "wrap" your JSX file into a project:

Create the structure:

Bash
npm create vite@latest my-project -- --template react
Move your code:
Copy the code from your existing JSX file and paste it into the new src/App.jsx file that was just created.

Push THIS folder to GitHub:
Delete the old files in your GitHub repo and upload the contents of this new my-project folder instead.

Step 3: Update Netlify Build Settings
Once your GitHub has the proper project structure (with a package.json), go back to your Netlify dashboard shown in the screenshot:

Click on Project configuration (on the left sidebar).

Find Build & deploy -> Continuous Deployment.

Click Edit settings and ensure they look like this:

Build command: npm run build

Publish directory: dist

Save and click Deploy site again.

Why it's failing right now:
When you look at your screenshot, the "Production" deploy finished, but it likely only uploaded a text file (your JSX). When you visit digitq.netlify.app, the server looks for index.html. Since it's not there, it shows the "404 Not Found" page.

