Gemini said
I see the problem! Your GitHub repository only has one single .jsx file.

Imagine a .jsx file is like a high-end engine. Right now, you've handed the engine to Netlify, but Netlify needs the entire car (the React framework, an HTML body, and the wheels) to actually drive (host) it.

Since you likely don't want to set up a complex coding environment on your computer right now, here is the absolute simplest way to fix this inside GitHub:

Step 1: Add a package.json file
This file tells Netlify to install React so it can understand your JSX.

In your GitHub repo (shown in your screenshot), click Add file > Create new file.

Name the file: package.json

Paste this exact code into the box:

JSON
{
  "name": "digitq-uat",
  "private": true,
  "version": "0.0.0",
  "type": "module",
  "scripts": {
    "dev": "vite",
    "build": "vite build",
    "preview": "vite preview"
  },
  "dependencies": {
    "react": "^18.2.0",
    "react-dom": "^18.2.0",
    "lucide-react": "latest"
  },
  "devDependencies": {
    "@types/react": "^18.2.66",
    "@types/react-dom": "^18.2.22",
    "@vitejs/plugin-react": "^4.2.1",
    "vite": "^5.2.0"
  }
}
Scroll down and click Commit changes.

Step 2: Add an index.html file
This is the "shell" that holds your code.

Click Add file > Create new file.

Name the file: index.html

Paste this exact code:

HTML
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8" />
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0" />
    <title>UAT Preview</title>
  </head>
  <body>
    <div id="root"></div>
    <script type="module" src="/main.jsx"></script>
  </body>
</html>
Click Commit changes.

Step 3: Add a main.jsx file
This "bridges" your specific file to the HTML.

Click Add file > Create new file.

Name the file: main.jsx

Paste this (replace overview_screen_v_5_intelligence_led with your actual file name if it differs slightly):

JavaScript
import React from 'react'
import ReactDOM from 'react-dom/client'
import App from './overview_screen_v_5_intelligence_led.jsx'

ReactDOM.createRoot(document.getElementById('root')).render(
  <React.StrictMode>
    <App />
  </React.StrictMode>,
)
Click Commit changes.

Step 4: Add a vite.config.js file
Click Add file > Create new file.

Name it: vite.config.js

Paste this:

JavaScript
import { defineConfig } from 'vite'
import react from '@vitejs/plugin-react'

export default defineConfig({
  plugins: [react()],
})
Click Commit changes.

Step 5: Refresh Netlify
Go back to your Netlify Dashboard.

It should detect the new files automatically and start a "Building" process.

If it doesn't start, go to Deploys and click Trigger deploy.

Wait for about 60 seconds. Once it says Published, click your digitq.netlify.app link again. It should now show your component!

